#compdef sqrible
# ============================================================================
# sqrible - generate Go code from Postgres table
#            schemas (Go, BSD-3-Clause)
#
# Author : Jérôme Lebel (jeromer)
# Upstream: https://github.com/jeromer/sqrible
#
# `sqrible` is a code generator that introspects a
# live PostgreSQL table's schema (via the
# information_schema + pg_catalog tables) and emits
# Go source code matching the table's column layout
# - typically used to keep Go data-model structs +
# query helpers in sync with database migrations
# without writing them by hand.
#
# Operational model:
#   1. Connect to PostgreSQL via libpq environment
#      variables (PGHOST, PGPORT, PGDATABASE,
#      PGUSER, PGPASSWORD, PGSSLMODE, ...)
#   2. Read the YAML config file (per-table template
#      assignments + custom type mappings)
#   3. Introspect the specified table via
#      `SELECT FROM information_schema.columns` +
#      `pg_catalog.pg_attribute` for primary key /
#      foreign key / index metadata
#   4. Apply the table-specific Go text/template
#      from the template directory
#   5. Print the generated Go code to stdout
#
# Usage:
#   sqrible -c <config.yaml> -t <table-name> \
#           -d <template-dir>
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag.* parsing; all three required):
#   -c <file>          - YAML configuration file path
#                         (defines per-table template
#                         mappings, custom type
#                         overrides, exclusions)
#   -t <name>          - target table name (must
#                         appear in config file)
#   -d <dir>           - directory containing the Go
#                         text/template files
#                         referenced by config
#
# Environment (libpq standard):
#   PGHOST                - PostgreSQL host
#   PGPORT                - PostgreSQL port (default
#                            5432)
#   PGDATABASE            - target database name
#   PGUSER                - login user
#   PGPASSWORD            - login password (or via
#                            ~/.pgpass)
#   PGSSLMODE             - disable / allow / prefer
#                            / require / verify-ca /
#                            verify-full
#   PGAPPNAME             - application name (default
#                            "sqrible")
#
# Example:
#   PGHOST=db.example.com \
#   PGDATABASE=production \
#   PGUSER=readonly \
#   sqrible -c sqrible.yaml -t users \
#           -d templates/go > internal/models/users.go
#
# The pgx lane is built on `github.com/jackc/pgx`
# (declared at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported as `github.com/jackc/pgx` then
# `pgx.Connect(pgConnConfig)` + `pgx.ParseEnvLibpq()`),
# the canonical Go PostgreSQL client by Jack
# Christensen (jackc) - github.com/jackc/pgx, 12000+
# stars on the v5 line.
#
# jackc/pgx is structurally unusual in the Go
# database driver ecosystem: it implements the
# PostgreSQL frontend/backend protocol v3 directly
# (no FFI to libpq) AND it implements the stdlib
# database/sql `driver.Driver` interface for
# compatibility with code written against the
# standard database/sql API. This dual-API design
# lets pgx serve two distinct use cases from one
# library:
#
#   - HIGH-PERFORMANCE PATH: use pgx's native APIs
#     (`pgx.Connect` + `conn.Query` + `pgx.RowToStructByName`)
#     to access protocol-level features
#     (parameterized COPY, binary-format value
#     marshaling, NOTIFY/LISTEN, PostgreSQL-specific
#     types like jsonb + ltree + hstore) without
#     database/sql overhead
#   - STDLIB-COMPAT PATH: import `pgx/stdlib` to
#     register pgx as a `database/sql` driver under
#     the standard `sql.Open("pgx", connstr)` API,
#     trading some throughput for compatibility with
#     ORM libraries + connection-pool libraries +
#     legacy code already written against
#     database/sql
#
# Christensen's library is the de-facto Go Postgres
# canonical - depended on by:
#   - GoLang's stdlib database/sql ecosystem (when
#     users prefer pgx over the older lib/pq driver)
#   - bun ORM, ent ORM, sqlc, GORM (when configured
#     with pgx as the underlying driver)
#   - hashicorp/vault's database secret engine
#   - PostgREST's Go reimplementation efforts
#   - sqrible (THIS BINARY)
#
# jackc/pgx replaced lib/pq as the canonical Go
# Postgres driver around 2020 - lib/pq (a port of
# the older Python libpq style) had been the
# canonical driver since 2013 but stopped accepting
# new features after the core team migrated focus to
# pgx for its broader feature coverage + maintained
# performance lead. lib/pq is now maintenance-only;
# new Go projects targeting Postgres almost universally
# use pgx.
#
# sqrible uses pgx in `connectPG()` via
# `pgx.ParseEnvLibpq()` to construct the connection
# from libpq environment variables, then
# `pgx.Connect(cfg)` to establish the connection.
# All schema introspection happens through pgx's
# `conn.Query` against the information_schema +
# pg_catalog catalogs.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 256 :: Postgres protocol (frontend/backend
#              wire-protocol v3) client libraries
# Round 1467 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 256
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : sfackler/rust-postgres      [R1466 _reth-database-reader]
#             umbrella
#   Go      : jackc/pgx                   [R1467 THIS FILE]
#             (replaced lib/pq as
#              canonical ~2020)
#   TS/Node : brianc/node-postgres        [R1468 closing]
#             (npm `pg`)
#
# jackc/pgx is structurally interesting because of
# its *dual-API library architecture*. The three
# lanes form a clean spectrum of Postgres-client
# implementation strategies:
#
#   - Rust (sfackler/rust-postgres umbrella):
#     split-by-concern umbrella with separate
#     postgres (sync) + tokio-postgres (async) +
#     postgres-protocol (codec) + postgres-types
#     (value conversions) crates; users compose the
#     subset they need
#   - Go (jackc/pgx): dual-API single library;
#     either use pgx's native APIs (perf path) OR
#     register pgx as a database/sql driver via
#     pgx/stdlib (stdlib-compat path); replaced
#     lib/pq as canonical ~2020
#   - Node (brianc/node-postgres): single API
#     surface (`pg` package's `Client` + `Pool` +
#     `Cursor` classes); fewer optionalities than
#     the Rust + Go canonicals but most-trodden
#     Node API surface since 2010
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# Postgres protocol v3 frontend message stream
# produced by rust-postgres + pgx + node-postgres is
# byte-identical to PostgreSQL server's expected wire
# format. All three lanes pass the same PostgreSQL
# protocol conformance test corpus.
# ============================================================================

_sqrible() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-c[YAML configuration file path]:file:_files -g "*.{yaml,yml}"' \
        '-t[target table name]:table:' \
        '-d[template directory]:dir:_files -/' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]'
}

_sqrible "$@"
